FSI Application Architecture Standard: Technical Governance Handbook

1. Architectural Vision and Governance Framework

The strategic importance of a unified architecture across the Freight Services Inc. (FSI) ecosystem is paramount for maintaining a high-velocity, resilient software portfolio. The FSI Technical Governance Standard mandates a stack unified on Flask, SQLAlchemy, and Google Cloud Run. This standardization is the primary mechanism for mitigating technical debt and ensuring operational scalability across all business units. By enforcing these common frameworks, FSI ensures that engineers can move between projects with zero friction, deployment cycles remain predictable, and the organization can scale its infrastructure horizontally without reinventing core logic.

All engineering decisions must be rooted in three non-negotiable Architectural Pillars:

* Clarity: Repositories must be self-documenting. Every architectural pattern—from table naming to service abstraction—must serve the goal of making the codebase instantly navigable for any FSI engineer.
* Consistency: Patterns for data persistence, transactional messaging, and visual branding are standardized. There is a "single way" to build FSI software to prevent environment drift and fragmentation.
* Secure-by-Default: Security is a runtime requirement, not an audit item. This is enforced through mandatory secret management, the elimination of local credential storage, and the adoption of client-side processing for sensitive document handling.

Compliance with the technical requirements defined in this handbook is mandatory for all applications within the FSI ecosystem.


